  "method": "We propose UniX-CL, a semi-supervised cross-modal contrastive framework that turns abundant unimodal images and texts into supervisory signal via teacher-guided listwise distillation, semantic-controlled counterfactuals, and a distributional alignment regularizer. UniX-CL uses two lightweight student encoders (image and text) with modality-specific projectors into a shared embedding space. A strong, frozen vision–language teacher (e.g., a CLIP-like model) provides cross-modal rankings over large, unpaired corpora. Training interleaves three data streams: scarce paired (image, text), unpaired images, and unpaired texts.\n\nFirst, we bootstrap strong unimodal representations. For images, we train the student with instance-level contrastive learning on augmented views and produce k “views” per image using learnable viewer tokens that yield multiple embeddings per sample; a max-aggregation over these embeddings preserves ANN-friendly retrieval while capturing diverse semantics. For text, we combine SimCSE-style augmentation with semantic-controlled edits to create positive (meaning-preserving) and hard-negative (meaning-altering) pairs; this toughens the text encoder without needing image matches.\n\nSecond, we convert unpaired corpora into cross-modal supervision with teacher-guided listwise distillation. For each unpaired image, we use the frozen teacher to retrieve and rank M candidate texts from the unpaired text pool; symmetrically, texts retrieve images. The student is trained to reproduce these orderings with a listwise/pairwise RankNet-style objective built on its cosine scores over the same candidate sets. This listwise signal is stronger than single positive–negative pairs and remains well-defined without numeric teacher scores. As training progresses, we mine pseudo-positives by keeping top-1 or mutual top-K neighbors with high teacher–student agreement and use them in a multi-positive InfoNCE with in-batch negatives and soft weights from the teacher.\n\nThird, we add a factual–counterfactual contrastive objective to exploit unimodal augmentations for cross-modal alignment. For each real or pseudo-positive (image, text), we generate meaning-preserving textual edits (e.g., tense/voice changes, function-word deletions) that should keep similarity high, and counterfactual edits that flip key attributes or objects and must reduce similarity. On the vision side, we compute teacher-guided saliency; masking background yields factual image views that should maintain similarity, while masking salient regions forms counterfactuals that should lower it. We enforce margin-separated similarities across these variants, sharpening the student’s sensitivity to truly grounding content.\n\nFinally, we stabilize the joint space with a copula-based dependency regularizer. Over batches of matched real and pseudo-positives, we model the joint of image/text embeddings via a parametric copula (e.g., Gaussian copula) atop flexible marginals. Maximizing the copula likelihood alongside contrastive losses encourages the student to capture higher-order cross-modal dependencies beyond cosine similarity, improving robustness when pair supervision is thin. Training alternates mini-batches from the three streams and linearly ramps up pseudo-positive weight as teacher–student NDCG improves. At inference, we index all viewer embeddings per image and use max similarity to a text query (and vice versa), preserving first-stage retrieval efficiency.",
  "rationale": "Scarce paired data limits classical contrastive alignment, but abundant unimodal corpora can be turned into cross-modal supervision if we can (i) produce reliable cross-modal orderings, (ii) generate hard positives/negatives that target grounding, and (iii) prevent collapse to superficial correlations. Teacher-guided listwise distillation supplies rich relative preferences over large candidate sets without requiring ground-truth pairs, letting the student learn from unpaired images and texts at scale. Multi-view embeddings expand each sample’s semantic coverage, reducing missed matches under weak pairing.\n\nSemantic-controlled textual edits and saliency-driven visual masks provide factual and counterfactual variants that inject precise, alignment-aware contrastive signals from unimodal data, improving grounding sensitivity. A copula regularizer complements similarity losses by explicitly fitting cross-modal dependence structure, yielding a better-posed joint space under limited direct supervision. Together, these components transform unpaired data into effective cross-modal training signals while preserving efficiency for retrieval and transfer.",
