  "method": "We propose UniX-Align, a semi-supervised contrastive framework that learns cross-modal image–text representations by leveraging abundant unimodal corpora and a small set of aligned pairs. Two modality-specific encoders are first pretrained with strong unimodal self-supervision (e.g., image contrastive learning and sentence-level contrastive learning) and then connected via a shared semantic prototype bank. Each encoder projects samples to a common embedding and outputs a soft assignment over K shared prototypes; the modality-specific projection heads remain distinct, while the prototype bank is shared to anchor a joint semantic space. A lightweight confidence head attached to the prototype layer provides per-sample uncertainty used to weight noisy supervision signals.\n\nTo turn unimodal data into useful cross-modal supervision, we mine pseudo pairs with two complementary channels. First, we build a cross-modal pivot space using visual taggers for images and keyword/entity extraction for text, and connect samples with high tag-overlap; a general-domain teacher (e.g., CLIP) provides soft similarity scores as additional weak signals, but these are down-weighted by the confidence head and an uncertainty-guided EMA schedule so that only stable pseudo links accumulate influence over time. Second, we construct set-level training tuples by sampling small groups of images and texts that share coarse tags. We then apply a permutation-invariant, set-to-set contrastive objective that encourages correct within-set assignments to score higher than mismatched ones, together with an auxiliary “mix-and-separate” prediction that asks the model to recover which text in the set is most responsible for each image (and vice versa). This disambiguates associations without requiring exact instance-level labels upfront.\n\nTraining follows a coarse-to-fine curriculum. We begin by aligning prototype distributions at the cluster level: separately cluster unimodal embeddings, link clusters via tag overlap and teacher scores, and minimize cross-modal divergence between their prototype assignments while preserving high-entropy, diverse usage of prototypes. As pseudo pairs stabilize, we transition to instance-level contrastive training on high-confidence matches, interleaving: (a) supervised InfoNCE on the scarce true pairs, (b) confidence-weighted InfoNCE on pseudo pairs, (c) the set-to-set mix-and-separate loss, and (d) a structure-preserving term that encourages local neighborhood consistency across modalities so that unimodal proximity is reflected cross-modally. A memory bank maintains embeddings and tag metadata to refresh pseudo neighbors periodically; pseudo-pair weights are updated with an uncertainty-aware EMA so noisy links decay while consistent links grow.\n\nAt convergence, both encoders and the shared prototype bank define an aligned space suitable for retrieval and transfer. Inference uses standard cosine similarity between image and text embeddings, with optional prototype-temperature calibration learned during training to improve zero-shot retrieval in the low-pair regime.",
  "rationale": "The core challenge is to exploit plentiful unimodal data without reliable alignment. UniX-Align converts unimodal corpora into usable cross-modal signals in two ways: (1) prototype-anchored alignment that ties both modalities to a common semantic scaffold learned at scale from unimodal pretraining, and (2) pseudo supervision that is robust to noise through set-level mix-and-separate objectives, confidence weighting, and an uncertainty-guided EMA curriculum. This lets the model learn which image features go with which textual concepts even when exact pairings are sparse.\n\nSet-to-set training leverages weak co-occurrence and topical similarity to create contrastive pressure without requiring instance-level pairs, while the confidence-weighted EMA and prototype-based uncertainty mitigate confirmation bias from imperfect teachers and noisy taggers. The curriculum from cluster-level to instance-level alignment further reduces brittleness: the model first learns broad cross-modal semantics before committing to fine-grained matches, improving stability and final retrieval performance under scarce paired supervision.",
